file_profiles.summary: Excel workbook containing DSC business plan data. Sheet-level analysis is required to understand specific content and schema within each sheet. Will extract sheet names, column headers, data types, and sample rows.

metric_significance.Revenue: Represents the total income generated by DSC from its business activities. A critical indicator of market demand and sales effectiveness. Tracking revenue growth is essential for assessing the overall performance and trajectory of the business plan.
metric_significance.Expenses: Encompasses all costs incurred by DSC in operating its business, including cost of goods sold (COGS), operating expenses (OPEX), marketing expenses, and administrative costs. Understanding expense drivers is crucial for identifying areas where costs can be optimized and profitability improved. Monitoring expenses against budget is essential for financial control.
metric_significance.Profit Margins (Gross & Net): Gross profit margin reflects the percentage of revenue remaining after deducting the cost of goods sold (COGS), indicating the profitability of DSC's core operations. Net profit margin represents the percentage of revenue remaining after deducting all expenses, providing a comprehensive measure of overall profitability. Analyzing trends in profit margins helps assess the efficiency of DSC's operations and its ability to generate profit.
metric_significance.Customer Acquisition Cost (CAC): Represents the total cost incurred to acquire a new customer, including marketing and sales expenses. Monitoring CAC is essential for evaluating the efficiency of DSC's customer acquisition strategies. A high CAC may indicate inefficient marketing campaigns or ineffective sales processes, while a low CAC suggests successful customer acquisition efforts. Analyzing CAC in relation to customer lifetime value (LTV) helps assess the long-term profitability of acquiring new customers.

key_metrics_T002.analysis_notes: This analysis assumes the 'DSC Business Plan - Mar.xlsx' contains sheets outlining financial projections. A detailed analysis of the actual sheets and columns would be required to identify specific KPIs related to each metric (e.g., revenue by product line, marketing spend by campaign).
